jobs.description:
Legal Counsel to Australian Unity’s Independent & Assisted Living business, which is a provider of community-based care, disability, dental and allied health services, and operator of retirement villages and aged care facilities.

Responsibilities include: 
• drafting commercial contracts; 
• dispute resolution, litigation and leading responses to regulatory investigations; 
• reviewing operational and marketing materials; 
• providing timely commercial advice; 
• assisting with tenders and projects; 
• preparing learning and development materials; 
• supporting corporate governance and compliance matters.

I assisted clients in the resolution of a broad range of general commercial disputes. Areas of law advised on included contractual claims, negligence, misleading or deceptive conduct, consumer law, joint ventures, partnerships, insolvency, directors' duties, and equitable claims. I worked with clients in a broad spectrum of industries and acted for publicly listed companies, private companies and individuals. 

Key skills included:
• managing small to medium sized litigation and assisting as part of a team on larger proceedings;
• mediation, negotiation and trial preparation; 
• drafting various court documents;
• liaising directly with various stakeholders in litigation including clients, opposing solicitors, the court, counsel, witnesses and experts.

I also gained valuable transactional experience working in the firm's Projects and Banking & Finance divisions.

Further, I volunteered as a pro bono lawyer and advocate for the Homeless Persons Legal Clinic (HPLC) run by Justice Connect as part of my employment. The HPLC is a specialist legal service that offers free legal assistance to women who are homeless or at risk of homelessness and/or victims of domestic violence. I negotiated the settlement of tenancy disputes, appeared as an advocate before tribunals, drafted submissions, and worked directly with clients, tribunals, social workers and other interested parties.

Noble Lawyers is a commercial law firm specialising in building, construction and contract law. The firm acts for builders, contractors, sub-contractors, project managers, developers, architects and home owners. 

Key experience included: 
• preparing for trials and appeals; 
• legal research; 
• drafting court documents;
• preparing interlocutory applications;
• drafting letters of demand, statutory demands and proofs of debt;
• facilitating the settlement of disputes;
• briefing counsel.

Solicitor in the Dispute Resolution group with particular experience in: 

 - large class actions;
 - tax disputes;
 - corporate governance; 
 - white-collar crime; and
 - public law.

Volunteer Solicitor at the "Women's Homelessness Prevention Project". The project assists women at risk of homelessness in resolving tenancy issues.

Experience includes:

•managing client files relating to possession and compensation claims (private and public tenancy);
•VCAT appearance work;
•liaising with social workers to ensure clients receive assistance with non-legal issues.

Experience includes:

• Drafting contractual documents for Aboriginal community development projects in Central Australia;

•Researching impacts of policy on Indigenous groups;

•Attending contract negotiation and consultation meetings with Indigenous community leaders in remote communities.

Experience in:

•Preparing client advice folders, taking legal instructions, drafting advice letters (civil and criminal matters), drafting letters of demand;

•Communicating legal concepts to clients unfamiliar with the Australian legal system.

Experience in:

•Coordinating an HIV/AIDS awareness school education program based South Africa;

•Maintaining overseas aid project related documentation including proposals, submissions, funding schedules and requests and project updates.

Experience in:

•Editing official country reports for use by the High Commissioner;

•Developing public relation skills in a diplomatic environment;

I have experience with a broad range of matters, including:
• private M&A transactions;
• public takeovers;
• initial public offerings;
• cross border transactions;
• shareholder arrangements;
• corporate restructures; 
• corporate governance; and 
• commercial contracts.

I have worked with clients in the financial services, funds management, energy, logistics, infrastructure, agriculture and consumer product sectors. 

I completed a six month rotation in the Disputes (Commercial Litigation) practice group in 2014. 

I also completed a six month client secondment at ANZ in the Australia Legal Group in 2017.

Yilong is a solicitor in the Commercial Litigation team of Herbert Smith Freehills. He has worked a number of matters in trial and appellate courts in several jurisdictions, including:
•	appearing before the Victorian Court of Appeal on the issue of costs;
•	advising clients on FOI requests and review;
•	restraint of trade proceedings in the Supreme Court of New South Wales;
•	the defence of a class action brought against Newcrest Mining in the Federal Court of Australia; 
•	for Boral Resources in its successful defence of an application for special leave by the CFMEU in the High Court of Australia.

Yilong also has secondment experience with Telstra, and General Atomics, a defence contractor based in the United States.

Yilong has also worked on a number of transactions, including:
•	the $1.2 billion initial public offering of Inghams Group Limited;
•	successful applications to the Foreign Investment Review Board applications for an ASX-listed A-REIT for sensitive land acquisitions; and
•	the demerger of South32 by BHP Billiton Limited and BHP Limited Plc.

Yilong holds a Bachelor of Arts (Advanced)(Honours I) degree from the University of Sydney, and a Juris Doctor from the University of Melbourne.  He has been with Herbert Smith Freehills since 2015.
He is admitted to practise as a solicitor of the Supreme Court of Victoria, the Federal Court of Australia and the High Court of Australia.

Publications:
- Julian Lincoln and Yilong Li, 'Summary of Veda 2015 "Cybercrime and Fraud Report"' [2016] Vol 19 (No 3) Internet Law Bulletin 314

Yilong was significantly involved in the following matters:
•	Environinvest Ltd (Receivers & Managers Appt)(In Liq) & Ors v The Former Partnership of Webster, White, Gridley, Nairn, Newman, Peters and Miller t/a HLB Mann Judd (Vic Partnership) [2012] FCA 1307;
•	Environinvest Ltd (Receivers & Managers Appt)(In Liq) & Ors v Pescott & Ors; Environinvest Ltd (Receivers & Managers Appt)(In Liq) & Ors v Blackburne Pty Ltd & Ors (No 2) [2012] VSC 151;
•	Mainfreight International Pty Ltd v Trailer Corporation of Australia Pty Ltd [2012] FCA 922;
•	Berger v Lysteron Pty Ltd & Ors [2012] VSC 95.

- Commenced PhD research with an Australian Postgraduate Award in contemporary Chinese art;
- Taught first year introductory art history subject and senior advanced course on French Post-Impressionism;
- Panelist with Georgia Wallace-Crabbe at the Chinese Documentary Film Conference at USyd (2010); presented at Pechakucha in conjunction with the Sydney Biennale in 2010 (“The Aesthetics of Emptiness: the Void in Contemporary Art”).

Working in a team of 4 lawyers advising on the management of 14,000+ employees, I provide in-house advice, assist with litigation (conciliation), as well as devise and deliver regular training on the following, but not limited to:
- unfair dismissal and adverse action claims under the Fair Work Act 2009;
- claims under the Safety, Rehabilitation and Compensation Act 1988;
- compliance with work (occupational) health and safety laws, particularly the the Work, Health and Safety Act 2011 (Cth);
- compliance with the Public Government, Performance and Accountability Act 2013;
- complex statutory interpretation;
- administrative decision making broadly, and specifically in a rehabilitation case management context;
- freedom of information and privacy;
- Code of Conduct (disciplinary) matters in the Australian Pubic Service;
- responding to protected industrial action under the Fair Work Act;
- breaches of common law contracts of employment;
- estoppel in employment contracts;
- restraint of trade clauses;
- drafting deeds of settlement and release;
- compliance with the Legal Services Directions 2005 (for government model litigants);
- litigation in the Federal Courts;
- some debt recovery;
- compensation claims in a government context (tort liability for negligent misrepresentation and compensation for damage from defective administration); and
- managing chronic absenteeism and underperformance in a public sector context.

As a Legal Officer in Migration Litigation, I managed the conduct of migration and litigation matters in the Australian federal courts, and internal responses to litigation developments. 

Fixed term contract(s).

